--- title: "Macalester College student Majors" image: majors.jpg image-alt: "Screenshot of enrollment in Major Categories (Male) ." categories: - Collaboration - Education about: template: solana image: majors.jpg --- In collaboration with two classmates in our intro to data science course, we centered our final project around differences in declared majors at Macalester College between Men and Woman We did a lot of data wrangling to find answers to our question, which was, is there a difference between men and woman, in terms of majors/field one joins and has this changed throughout time. Below will be my code for my parts in this project ###Collaborators Lindsay Alaniz, Sicy Wang, and Elinai Alicia Severiano Perez ###Products ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(tidyverse) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ── Attaching core tidyverse packages ──────────────────────── tidyverse 2.0.0 ── ✔ dplyr 1.1.3 ✔ readr 2.1.4 ✔ forcats 1.0.0 ✔ stringr 1.5.0 ✔ ggplot2 3.4.3 ✔ tibble 3.2.1 ✔ lubridate 1.9.2 ✔ tidyr 1.3.0 ✔ purrr 1.0.2 ── Conflicts ────────────────────────────────────────── tidyverse_conflicts() ── ✖ dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter() ✖ dplyr::lag() masks stats::lag() ℹ Use the conflicted package () to force all conflicts to become errors ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} library(ggplot2) library(lubridate) library(plotly) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Attaching package: 'plotly' The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2': last_plot The following object is masked from 'package:stats': filter The following object is masked from 'package:graphics': layout ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} library(tidyverse) majordata <- read_csv("majordatacopy.csv") ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Rows: 2444 Columns: 64 ── Column specification ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── Delimiter: "," chr (12): grad_year, sex, first_gen, admit_type, major1, major2, major3, maj... dbl (52): StudentID, terms_enrl_ct, studied_away, major_ct, maj_Art, maj_Mus... ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data. ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message. ``` ::: ::: **Major Divisions** For this part I looked into the five major divisions: Social Sciences, Natural Sciences and Mathematics, Humanities, Interdisciplinary, and Fine Arts. I compared them over the years and a graph for women and one for men. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} majordata14 <- majordata %>% select(grad_year, major1_division ,sex) %>% filter(sex=="F")%>% na.omit() %>% group_by(grad_year, major1_division) %>% summarize(total = sum(n())) %>% mutate(percentage = 100*total/sum(total)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` `summarise()` has grouped output by 'grad_year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument. ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} library(plotly) p <- ggplot(majordata14, aes(x= grad_year, y =percentage, color=major1_division)) + geom_point(aes(shape=major1_division )) + geom_line(aes(group = major1_division , color=major1_division)) + labs(x=NULL, y= NULL) + scale_color_manual(values = c("coral4", "darkorange3", "darkgoldenrod2" , "darkcyan", "darkolivegreen"))+ ggtitle("Macalester College | Major Divisions\nPercentage of Females per Major Division & Year") + theme_classic()+ annotate("text", x= "2013-14", y=31, label="Social Sciences", color="darkolivegreen") + annotate("text", x= "2016-17", y=24, label="Natural Sciences and Mathematics", color="darkcyan") + annotate("text", x= "2013-14", y=19, label="Humanities", color="darkorange3") + annotate("text", x= "2013-14", y=12, label="Interdisciplinary", color="darkgoldenrod2") + annotate("text", x= "2013-14", y=2, label="Fine Arts", color="coral4") + theme(legend.position= "none") + theme(text = element_text(family = "Times New Roman")) ggplotly(p) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} majordata14.0 <- majordata %>% select(grad_year, major1_division ,sex) %>% filter(sex=="M")%>% na.omit() %>% group_by(grad_year, major1_division) %>% summarize(total = sum(n())) %>% mutate(percentage = 100*total/sum(total)) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` `summarise()` has grouped output by 'grad_year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument. ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} p1 <- ggplot(majordata14.0, aes(x= grad_year, y =percentage, color=major1_division )) + geom_point(aes(shape=major1_division)) + geom_line(aes(group = major1_division , color=major1_division)) + labs(x=NULL, y= NULL) + scale_color_manual(values = c("coral4", "darkorange3", "darkgoldenrod2" , "darkcyan", "darkolivegreen"))+ ggtitle("Macalester College | Major Divisions \nPercentage of Males per Major Division & Year") + theme_classic()+ annotate("text", x= "2013-14", y=40, label="Social Sciences", color="darkolivegreen") + annotate("text", x= "2014-15", y=27, label="Natural Sciences and Mathematics", color="darkcyan") + annotate("text", x= "2014-15", y=15, label="Humanities", color="darkorange3") + annotate("text", x= "2017-18", y=8, label="Interdisciplinary", color="darkgoldenrod2") + annotate("text", x= "2013-14", y=2, label="Fine Arts", color="coral4") + theme(legend.position= "none") + theme(text = element_text(family = "Times New Roman")) ggplotly(p1) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: **Concentrations** For this part I looked into the different concentrations offered at Macalester and the enrollment between men and women. Further, I looked into first concentration (as in the first declared by a student) and second concentration ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} conc <- majordata %>% filter(concentration_ct == "1" ) p2 <-conc %>% ggplot(aes(x = sex, fill = Conc1Desc)) + geom_bar(position = 'fill') + scale_fill_manual(values = c("coral4", "darkkhaki", "darkgoldenrod2" , "burlywood", "darkolivegreen", "darkslategrey", "darkcyan" , "cornflowerblue" , "antiquewhite4" , "darkorange3" , "darkorchid" , "darkseagreen" , "deeppink4")) + labs(x=NULL, y= NULL , fill= "Concentrations") + ggtitle("Macalester College | First Concentration \n Percentage of Female & Male in their first concentrations ") + theme_classic() + theme(text = element_text(family = "Times New Roman")) ggplotly(p2) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} conc2 <- majordata %>% filter(concentration_ct == "2" ) p3 <-conc2 %>% ggplot(aes(x=sex, fill= Conc2Desc)) + geom_bar(position = 'fill') + scale_fill_manual(values = c("coral4", "darkgoldenrod2" , "burlywood", "darkolivegreen", "darkslategrey", "darkcyan" , "darkorange3")) + labs(x=NULL, y= NULL , fill= "Concentrations") + ggtitle("Macalester College | Second Concentration \n Percentage of Female & Male in their second concentrations ") + theme_minimal() + theme(text = element_text(family = "Times New Roman")) ggplotly(p3) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: **Term Enrollment** Finally, I looked into the different lengths of term enrollments between men and women, but more specifically, by major division ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} term.enr <- majordata%>% filter(major1_division %in% c("Fine Arts" , "Humanities" , "Interdisciplinary" , "Natural Sciences and Mathematics" , "Social Sciences")) p5 <- term.enr %>% ggplot(aes(x=terms_enrl_ct)) + geom_density(aes(fill=sex) , alpha=0.5) + facet_wrap(~major1_division) + scale_fill_manual(values = c( "violetred4", "seagreen4"))+ labs(x=NULL, y= NULL, title = "Term Enrollment Distribution", subtitle = "Term Enrollment per major division and gender") + theme_classic() + theme(text = element_text(family = "Times New Roman")) ggplotly(p5) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning: Removed 77 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_density()`). ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
